00:02:00.820 --> 00:02:11.059
July 31, 2012 was the day that we first showed Shiny to the world. We were at JSM, not even

00:02:11.059 --> 00:02:15.580
a scheduled talk. Brian Lewis just lent us ten minutes at the end of his talk, and we

00:02:15.580 --> 00:02:24.580
showed Shiny. And if you consider that date, July 31, to be the birth of Shiny, then this

00:02:24.580 --> 00:02:31.300
is a particularly special talk for me to give to you today. Because that means that Shiny

00:02:31.300 --> 00:02:34.300
is ten years old.

00:02:34.300 --> 00:02:35.300
--

00:02:35.300 --> 00:02:49.460
Ten years. Hard to believe. So, to mark this anniversary, I thought I'd do things a little

00:02:49.460 --> 00:02:55.699
bit different this time than usual. I usually focus on what's coming, what's new, and I

00:02:55.699 --> 00:02:59.699
wanted to take this opportunity to talk a little bit about how Shiny started.

00:02:59.699 --> 00:03:08.500
And the story of how Shiny started really begins with Danny Kaplan. Oh, yeah, some Danny

00:03:08.500 --> 00:03:11.619
fans in the audience?

00:03:11.619 --> 00:03:12.619
--

00:03:13.619 --> 00:03:23.619
Danny and his students were the very first beta testers of RStudio IDE. This is going way

00:03:23.619 --> 00:03:31.619
better than I thought it would. And Danny's feedback was so great, his fingerprints are all

00:03:31.619 --> 00:03:36.619
over the IDE even to this day. You can see all the parts that he influenced with his feedback.

00:03:36.619 --> 00:03:44.619
And in early 2011, Danny asked JJ for a way to build interactive apps in R that he could

00:03:44.619 --> 00:03:55.619
use to demonstrate statistical and calculus concepts. And JJ being JJ, in about a week,

00:03:55.619 --> 00:04:05.619
he built this. This is the manipulate feature in RStudio. Sort of the proto-Shiny, if you

00:04:05.619 --> 00:04:13.619
will. And manipulate is great because it almost couldn't be simpler. This is how manipulate

00:04:13.619 --> 00:04:22.619
works. You give it some kind of plot-generating function or plot-generating expression and

00:04:22.619 --> 00:04:29.619
include one or more unbound variables that you want the user to be able to control.

00:04:29.619 --> 00:04:35.619
Then for each of those, you describe how you want that to appear. So there are a couple

00:04:35.619 --> 00:04:42.619
of, there's slider and there's lookup, a couple of things like that. And this worked great

00:04:42.619 --> 00:04:50.619
and Danny ran with it and created quite a few really beautifully thought out and assembled

00:04:50.619 --> 00:04:57.619
tiny applets that illustrated these concepts. And he bundled them together as part of this

00:04:57.619 --> 00:05:04.619
project, Mosaic. Now, it wasn't long, as tends to happen with software, it wasn't long before

00:05:04.619 --> 00:05:10.619
some questions started. Boy, it sure would be nice to have a customizable layout. Can

00:05:10.619 --> 00:05:16.619
I have those inputs show up in two columns, for example? Could I have more input types?

00:05:16.619 --> 00:05:21.619
Maybe multiple outputs at once instead of just one plot. Maybe different kinds of outputs

00:05:21.619 --> 00:05:26.619
like tables. And maybe instead of just showing things, we could also take some actions when

00:05:26.619 --> 00:05:33.619
the user clicked a button or something like that. And finally, why do people have to be

00:05:33.619 --> 00:05:38.619
using RStudio IDE to use these applets? It would be great to be able to take these little

00:05:38.619 --> 00:05:45.619
interactive things and move them out. All of those totally reasonable. Totally reasonable,

00:05:45.619 --> 00:05:53.619
great suggestions. And what he was describing was a full interactive UI framework. Now,

00:05:53.619 --> 00:06:00.619
that was something that JJ and I clearly had the technical ability to create. But I felt

00:06:00.619 --> 00:06:07.619
really strongly this is not something that we should do. This felt like a trap to me.

00:06:07.619 --> 00:06:14.619
Because UI programming sucks. This is how I honestly felt in 2012. I had spent a lot

00:06:14.619 --> 00:06:22.619
of my career writing complex UIs. And the reason it sucks is because of this idiom called

00:06:22.619 --> 00:06:31.619
event handlers. This is the way all UI worked in those days. The way event handlers work

00:06:31.619 --> 00:06:38.619
is so simple. I can explain it to you right now. The idea is this. When X happens, do

00:06:39.619 --> 00:06:47.619
Y. In this example, X being that some text box has changed. And in response, we want

00:06:47.619 --> 00:06:55.619
to do Y, which is update the text of this status label to some new value. Very, very

00:06:55.619 --> 00:07:03.619
simple. The problem is when you have multiple of these in your UI, they become hard to reason

00:07:03.619 --> 00:07:08.619
about. Similar to global variables. If you've ever been warmed off of programming with extensive

00:07:08.619 --> 00:07:15.619
use of global variables, it's the reasoning that becomes hard. And this is a huge problem

00:07:15.619 --> 00:07:21.619
because as your UI gets more complex and the logic gets more complex, it starts requiring

00:07:21.619 --> 00:07:26.619
extremely high levels of skill and discipline to do well. It can be done. Clearly, we've

00:07:27.619 --> 00:07:33.619
had complex UIs for a long time, but it really is deceptively difficult and takes the most

00:07:33.619 --> 00:07:39.619
disciplined and talented engineers. And if you don't get it quite right, if you don't

00:07:39.619 --> 00:07:44.619
have that level of skill and discipline, you end up with bugs. And not just normal bugs

00:07:44.619 --> 00:07:50.619
like freezing and errors, but more pernicious ones. Like an app confidently giving you an

00:07:50.619 --> 00:07:57.619
answer that's incorrect. And that's bad enough in a normal piece of consumer software, but

00:07:57.619 --> 00:08:03.619
to inflict that onto the R community? To put the tools into their hands to confidently

00:08:03.619 --> 00:08:13.619
get the wrong answer? It was unconscionable. So, we didn't do it. And the problem was,

00:08:13.619 --> 00:08:19.619
as much as I hated event handlers, I couldn't come up with not only a better alternative,

00:08:19.619 --> 00:08:24.619
but any alternative. I had been doing this kind of programming day in, day out for years.

00:08:24.619 --> 00:08:29.619
Constantly thinking there must be a better way than this. And I could not even conceive

00:08:29.619 --> 00:08:40.619
of a better way. Until around May of 2012. There's a lot of dates in this talk.

00:08:40.619 --> 00:08:48.619
In May of 2012, I watched a screen cast for a brand new web framework called Meteor.

00:08:49.619 --> 00:08:57.619
And this was the craziest thing I'd ever seen. It blew me away. There were so many ideas

00:08:57.619 --> 00:09:03.619
in Meteor that they were demonstrating in their code that felt like alien technology

00:09:03.619 --> 00:09:13.619
to me. Or like a magic trick. One particular magic trick among many just stuck itself in

00:09:13.619 --> 00:09:19.619
my brain, and I couldn't dislodge it, and it was this. Like any other web framework,

00:09:19.619 --> 00:09:25.619
Meteor had a way for you to have templates. You would write some HTML markup, and in the

00:09:25.619 --> 00:09:31.619
middle, you would throw in some dynamic value, like a name. And this is where, in a traditional

00:09:31.619 --> 00:09:35.619
web framework, you would then attach an event handler to make sure that that template was

00:09:35.619 --> 00:09:42.619
re-rendered at the appropriate time. But the Meteor guy said this verbatim. I changed

00:09:42.619 --> 00:09:48.619
the data and the template updates. There's no event handlers. It just works. And he said

00:09:48.619 --> 00:10:02.619
it like that. And I was like, there's no event handlers. It just works. What? Like, how?

00:10:02.619 --> 00:10:13.619
How does that just work? And that was me. I mean, for like days and maybe a week or

00:10:13.619 --> 00:10:19.619
two after, I couldn't shake this thought. How did they do that? And the only thing I

00:10:19.619 --> 00:10:23.619
could think of is maybe they just re-execute everything. Every time something changes,

00:10:23.619 --> 00:10:28.619
they just re-execute all of their templates, but that didn't seem to be what they were

00:10:28.619 --> 00:10:34.619
talking about. Finally, I couldn't take it anymore. I just went and Googled how does

00:10:34.619 --> 00:10:38.619
Meteor work. Don't worry, you're not supposed to be able to see the code here, but there

00:10:38.619 --> 00:10:43.619
was a Stack Overflow answer that pointed to this file and said this is how it works. And

00:10:43.619 --> 00:10:51.619
I just include the screenshot so that you can see how short it is. 71 lines of code

00:10:51.619 --> 00:11:00.619
with pretty copious comments. So I downloaded the Meteor repo onto my laptop and got on

00:11:00.619 --> 00:11:05.619
a plane ride home from a conference and I told myself, by the time I get off this plane,

00:11:05.619 --> 00:11:11.619
I'm going to understand how this works. And I did. It's actually pretty straightforward

00:11:11.619 --> 00:11:17.619
once you know the trick. It's simple, it's elegant, and it felt to me like maybe these

00:11:18.619 --> 00:11:22.619
guys are on to something. This is actually the better way to do this. Not just a trick,

00:11:22.619 --> 00:11:29.619
but a genuinely new way to do things. And I was very impressed, loved it, super satisfying

00:11:29.619 --> 00:11:35.619
to find out how it worked. And then I closed my laptop and, I don't know, watched a movie

00:11:35.619 --> 00:11:44.619
or something. No dots were connected that day. Shiny was not born that day.

00:11:44.619 --> 00:11:50.619
In fact, it was almost a month later when it finally hit me. And the way it hit me was

00:11:50.619 --> 00:11:57.619
a little weird. I swear this is true. This has never happened to me before or since.

00:11:57.619 --> 00:12:04.619
That morning I woke up. I opened my eyes and the very first conscious thought in my head

00:12:04.619 --> 00:12:10.619
was an entire web framework. Yeah, that's not a joke. That literally is what happened.

00:12:11.619 --> 00:12:19.619
And I will show you literally what it looked like. It started with a simple HTML interface.

00:12:19.619 --> 00:12:23.619
The most important thing was you weren't going to have to write any JavaScript as an app

00:12:23.619 --> 00:12:29.619
developer. All you had to do is write HTML tags and include IDs and classes that would

00:12:29.619 --> 00:12:36.619
indicate where inputs and outputs were and what they were called. And we would power

00:12:36.619 --> 00:12:44.619
that with reactive server logic using that trick from Meteor. All you would have to do

00:12:44.619 --> 00:12:50.619
is explain how an output is to be created based on these input values and Shiny would

00:12:50.619 --> 00:12:56.619
take care of knowing. You guys know how it works. Okay. And then a WebSocket connection

00:12:56.619 --> 00:13:01.619
to tie them both together. And this, what I'm showing, that was the first thought in

00:13:01.619 --> 00:13:09.619
my brain when I woke up that morning. It felt like a gift.

00:13:09.619 --> 00:13:15.619
But the weirdest thing about that morning wasn't necessarily the completeness of this

00:13:15.619 --> 00:13:25.619
vision. It was the timing. This is terrifying. I've never told this story in public, but

00:13:25.619 --> 00:13:30.619
I thought it was a thing that I really wanted to share with you now.

00:13:30.619 --> 00:13:39.619
That day, June 15, 2012, was supposed to be my last day at RStudio. That spring, I was

00:13:39.619 --> 00:13:50.619
just feeling like my voice is terrifying. That spring, I was feeling like my career

00:13:50.619 --> 00:13:57.619
had plateaued. I was a software engineer in my mid-30s. I loved the work that JJ and

00:13:57.619 --> 00:14:02.619
I were doing together, but it was just the two of us. And all around, I looked at my

00:14:02.619 --> 00:14:07.619
classmates and people that I had been peers with at past companies, and I saw them starting

00:14:07.619 --> 00:14:16.619
companies and riding rocket ships, you know, up the corporate ranks at the biggest tech

00:14:16.619 --> 00:14:22.619
companies and just doing the most amazing things that I would read about in the news.

00:14:22.619 --> 00:14:30.619
And I was deathly afraid of being left behind. And I felt like in order for me to feel like

00:14:30.619 --> 00:14:34.619
I was a success, I was going to need to start my own company.

00:14:34.619 --> 00:14:41.619
So I went to JJ. I mean, I've been with JJ for a long time, and I opened up to him about

00:14:41.619 --> 00:14:47.619
how I was feeling. And he said to me, I totally understand. And if that's what you want to

00:14:47.619 --> 00:14:51.619
do, I will support you. I'll help you however I can.

00:14:51.619 --> 00:14:58.619
But this was in the run-up to UseR. We were trying to get RMarkdown off the ground. He

00:14:58.619 --> 00:15:06.619
had a keynote. So my commitment to him was I'm going to fully focus on RStudio until

00:15:06.619 --> 00:15:11.619
UseR is over. And as soon as UseR is over, I'm going to go on leave and think about my

00:15:11.619 --> 00:15:16.619
future. And if all went well, I'd never come back from that leave.

00:15:16.619 --> 00:15:24.619
The last day of UseR, what did I say? June 15, 2012. It was that day. It was that day

00:15:24.619 --> 00:15:31.619
is my point. What was supposed to be my last day at RStudio.

00:15:32.619 --> 00:15:41.619
And in the blink of an eye, when this appeared in my brain, it was like a light switch was

00:15:41.619 --> 00:15:47.619
flipped. And all those feelings I had, all the fear and insecurity, were just erased

00:15:47.619 --> 00:15:57.619
in an instant. And I was completely consumed by this curiosity of would this work? Can

00:15:57.619 --> 00:16:06.619
we build this? And just filled with this creative drive to see this happen.

00:16:06.619 --> 00:16:12.619
And I tell this story because I want you to understand how profound a gift, really this

00:16:12.619 --> 00:16:17.619
was the first of many profound gifts that Shiny gave to me. I was about to make a pretty

00:16:17.619 --> 00:16:23.619
big life and career decision that I think would have been a mistake because I was making

00:16:23.619 --> 00:16:28.619
it out of fear and out of insecurity. And what Shiny gave me was something to run towards

00:16:28.619 --> 00:16:35.619
with curiosity, with creativity. And it's just been such a magical 10 years, I wouldn't

00:16:35.619 --> 00:16:37.619
trade it for anything.

00:16:37.619 --> 00:17:01.619
Oh, my gosh. Okay. Now, I took this sketch, you know, jotted it down and ran down to find

00:17:01.619 --> 00:17:09.619
JJ. And I showed him, I was like, look at this. And he immediately got it. I mean, instantly

00:17:09.619 --> 00:17:13.619
he was like, this is it. This is what you work on from now on. Forget everything else.

00:17:13.619 --> 00:17:20.619
You're working on this. And he just requested one change. It took him some time to convince

00:17:20.619 --> 00:17:26.619
me. He said, why are we making people write HTML? And I was like, I'm saving them from

00:17:26.619 --> 00:17:35.619
JavaScript. They can learn HTML. But he was pretty insistent, and he was very right. And

00:17:35.619 --> 00:17:41.619
what we ended up was this. Writing R on both the client and the server. Of course, you

00:17:41.619 --> 00:17:49.619
can use HTML if you want to. But this is pretty much what we have today in Shiny.

00:17:49.619 --> 00:17:58.619
So, with this idea in hand, we spent a frantic seven weeks making Shiny into a proof of concept

00:17:58.619 --> 00:18:03.619
that we could present at JSM. And seven weeks later, this is what we had. This is the demo

00:18:03.619 --> 00:18:10.619
that we displayed at JSM. And we had settled on a tagline that was easily create interactive

00:18:10.619 --> 00:18:15.619
web applications in R without needing to know HTML, JavaScript, and CSS.

00:18:15.619 --> 00:18:25.619
So, now we knew that it was possible. But now what? Now, to me, my ambitions for this

00:18:25.619 --> 00:18:32.619
was, gee, I hope someone uses this and likes it. And JJ being JJ said, why shouldn't all

00:18:32.619 --> 00:18:36.619
our users be making apps? And why shouldn't Shiny be the way that they make them?

00:18:37.619 --> 00:18:42.619
So, the three of us got to work. Winston Chang joined the company just a very short time

00:18:42.619 --> 00:18:49.619
after JSM, and we got to work working on Shiny. And in order for Shiny to be a success, for

00:18:49.619 --> 00:18:55.619
it to have an impact on the R community, there were three big questions that we had to answer,

00:18:55.619 --> 00:19:01.619
and the answers had to be yes across the board. The first question, can we even build this

00:19:02.619 --> 00:19:07.619
in R? We did the proof of concept, can we take it to production? Because the conventional

00:19:07.619 --> 00:19:14.619
wisdom was that R is a language for stats, not web frameworks. Secondly, are R users

00:19:14.619 --> 00:19:20.619
ready to write web apps? Because writing web apps is very different than data analysis.

00:19:20.619 --> 00:19:25.619
There are different muscles that you need to use. And Shiny in particular was going

00:19:26.619 --> 00:19:33.619
to ask people to learn concepts that nobody, almost nobody had seen before. Were R users

00:19:33.619 --> 00:19:40.619
ready to do that? And the third was, would the R community respond? In 2012, I mean,

00:19:43.619 --> 00:19:47.619
if you weren't there, it might be a little bit hard to picture, but we were nobodies.

00:19:47.619 --> 00:19:52.619
We were unknowns. And not only that, our studio, it was almost a little suspicious what we

00:19:53.619 --> 00:19:59.619
were doing. Here's this like weirdly fully formed IDE that they don't charge for. There's

00:19:59.619 --> 00:20:06.619
no pro version. They're working on it full time. So people were wondering, what's the

00:20:06.619 --> 00:20:13.619
catch? And especially in a community where the GPL and open source was so much part of

00:20:13.619 --> 00:20:21.619
the ethos, we wondered, are people going to accept us? I want to tackle these questions

00:20:21.619 --> 00:20:26.619
one by one, a little bit out of order. The first one being, are R users ready to write

00:20:26.619 --> 00:20:33.619
web apps? And what we learned was this. R users are not afraid to learn. I mean, think

00:20:33.619 --> 00:20:40.619
of who you need to be to even be considering learning Shiny. Okay. You learn statistics.

00:20:40.619 --> 00:20:46.619
You know about visualization. You learn to code. You know Git. You probably know the

00:20:46.619 --> 00:20:51.619
grammar of graphics. Yeah, I think they can sit through a few tutorials and read some

00:20:51.619 --> 00:20:57.619
reference documentation. R users were not afraid and continue to not be afraid. And

00:20:57.619 --> 00:21:03.619
R users were and are incredibly motivated by what Shiny offers them. We did not have

00:21:03.619 --> 00:21:08.619
to sell very hard for people to realize Shiny was not just one more tool in their toolbox,

00:21:08.619 --> 00:21:13.619
but it was a force multiplier for everything that they can already do in R. Because it

00:21:14.619 --> 00:21:19.619
meant those existing skills could be exposed to a broader audience than they could otherwise

00:21:19.619 --> 00:21:29.619
accomplish. And Shiny produced mic drop moments for R users. I'm going to go out a little

00:21:29.619 --> 00:21:35.619
bit on a limb here and tell me if this sounds familiar. I heard multiple stories of people

00:21:35.619 --> 00:21:40.619
going into a conference room with their Shiny app and leaving JAWS on the floor. I'm going

00:21:40.619 --> 00:21:44.619
to go out on a limb. Can I see a show of hands? Anyone have this experience? Written a Shiny

00:21:44.619 --> 00:21:53.619
app that, yeah, see, I'm not making it up. And that's a huge motivator for people. And

00:21:53.619 --> 00:21:57.619
something about Shiny feels within reach to R users, even though there are a lot of concepts

00:21:57.619 --> 00:22:03.619
that you need to learn. Somehow it feels like we wrote this for you. We wrote this expecting

00:22:03.619 --> 00:22:08.619
you to come along and learn it. And that felt different than TypeScript and React and these

00:22:08.619 --> 00:22:11.619
other web technologies where it felt like this was really for somebody else and you would

00:22:11.619 --> 00:22:19.619
have to become somebody else to learn this set of skills. And these things might almost

00:22:19.619 --> 00:22:28.619
seem obvious by now, but it wasn't back then. And in 2012 to 2015, there was like a Cambrian

00:22:28.619 --> 00:22:34.619
explosion of reactive frameworks in all different languages, and most of them are forgotten.

00:22:34.619 --> 00:22:39.619
Because most of them didn't find a user base that was motivated by what they had to offer

00:22:39.619 --> 00:22:44.619
or they couldn't make it past the learning curve. So I just want to be clear, I don't

00:22:44.619 --> 00:22:50.619
take this for granted. It's amazing. It's amazing that things worked out this way.

00:22:50.619 --> 00:22:55.619
So the question we had going into this is, are users ready to write web apps? And the

00:22:55.619 --> 00:23:03.619
conclusion that I've come to is that R has the best audience for Shiny. It's perfect.

00:23:03.619 --> 00:23:10.619
The next question, would the R community respond? And instead of telling you, let me

00:23:10.619 --> 00:23:20.619
just show you. This is just a list off the top of my head the other day of some of the

00:23:20.619 --> 00:23:25.619
many amazing packages that people have released that are built on top of Shiny and enhance

00:23:25.619 --> 00:23:29.619
the capabilities of Shiny in some way. And I know that a lot of you in this audience

00:23:29.619 --> 00:23:33.619
are using these packages, and the authors of some of these packages are here in the

00:23:33.619 --> 00:23:40.619
audience as well. Maintaining an open source package that people actually use is not an

00:23:40.619 --> 00:23:45.619
easy feat, and a lot of people put a lot of time into the packages, not only on this list,

00:23:45.619 --> 00:23:49.619
but on all the ones that I don't have room to list here. And again, I don't take that

00:23:49.619 --> 00:23:56.619
lightly. That is a huge vote of confidence in the work that we're doing and the foundation

00:23:56.619 --> 00:24:06.619
that we've built. So I'm so grateful to all these people, and there's a GitHub user called

00:24:06.619 --> 00:24:12.619
nanxstats that has a document called awesome Shiny extensions at GitHub. And this is a

00:24:12.619 --> 00:24:18.619
list of just a whole bunch of packages written in R that extend or enhance Shiny in some

00:24:18.619 --> 00:24:28.619
way. There's a few. Again, it's humbling to see how much time and energy people have

00:24:28.619 --> 00:24:38.619
invested in trying to make Shiny better. And as Hadley said, writing books ain't easy.

00:24:38.619 --> 00:24:45.619
I'm sorry, this is unscripted, but I believe the first advice you gave me about book writing

00:24:45.619 --> 00:24:50.619
was I asked, how does it work with getting a publisher or whatever? And he said, step

00:24:50.619 --> 00:25:01.619
one, write a book. Step two, get it published. There's no step three. Yeah. Not great advice.

00:25:01.619 --> 00:25:09.619
So I'm astounded that there are, I mean, not just three, but there are several more

00:25:09.619 --> 00:25:14.619
complete books that people have written about Shiny. And again, knowing how hard it is to

00:25:14.619 --> 00:25:21.619
put together a book, I'm in awe that there are people who are doing this for Shiny.

00:25:21.619 --> 00:25:26.619
I don't think we can really talk about the Shiny community without mentioning Eric Nance.

00:25:26.619 --> 00:25:29.619
Is Eric Nance around here somewhere? There he is.

00:25:29.619 --> 00:25:42.619
Yeah. Eric Nance might be the biggest cheerleader for Shiny inside or outside of our studio.

00:25:42.619 --> 00:25:49.619
And among the many contributions that Eric has made is he currently has the Shiny developer

00:25:49.619 --> 00:25:55.619
series going. It is, what, 30-plus episodes and counting of really interesting and deep

00:25:55.619 --> 00:26:00.619
conversations with very interesting and deep people around the Shiny community.

00:26:00.619 --> 00:26:04.619
So I definitely encourage you to check that out.

00:26:04.619 --> 00:26:11.619
And there are so many other ways people contribute that are not necessarily in those categories.

00:26:11.619 --> 00:26:18.619
Every GitHub issue or PR, it takes time and energy to put together reprexes, to put together

00:26:18.619 --> 00:26:22.619
patches, and I appreciate every single one.

00:26:22.619 --> 00:26:28.619
Every year we hold a Shiny contest, and I'm blown away by the amount of care people put

00:26:28.619 --> 00:26:33.619
into crafting these submissions. It clearly means a lot to people.

00:26:33.619 --> 00:26:39.619
Blog posts, conference talks, workshops, there's so much content that people put together

00:26:39.619 --> 00:26:44.619
about Shiny, and it is not easy.

00:26:44.619 --> 00:26:48.619
There are entire tutorials that were created by people in the community.

00:26:48.619 --> 00:26:54.619
Zev Ross here in the front row created a tutorial talking about how to use Shiny from scratch

00:26:54.619 --> 00:27:01.619
with a bent-towards-GG plot, and that got a lot of people into Shiny in the beginning.

00:27:01.619 --> 00:27:05.619
Appsalon, are the Appsalon guys here? The Appsalon folks?

