Didn't see that coming.

00:27:14.619 --> 00:27:18.619
So I'm sorry. You know, it's been ten years.

00:27:18.619 --> 00:27:22.619
Please, can you just give me this?

00:27:22.619 --> 00:27:26.619
I'm so grateful to all these people and all the different kinds of contributions they've made,

00:27:26.619 --> 00:27:30.619
and because I have the attention of this whole room, and I know a lot of the people in the community

00:27:30.619 --> 00:27:36.619
are in this room, can we just take a second and all say thank you to all these people?

00:27:36.619 --> 00:28:00.619
So the question was, will the R community respond?

00:28:00.619 --> 00:28:06.619
I can't even put into words how the community has responded.

00:28:06.619 --> 00:28:10.619
And finally, can we even build it in R?

00:28:10.619 --> 00:28:19.619
In 2012, you might have heard things like, R is a DSL, a domain-specific language.

00:28:19.619 --> 00:28:26.619
The alternative to R isn't Python or C Sharp. It's SAS.

00:28:26.619 --> 00:28:30.619
Or use R for, you know, a web server.

00:28:30.619 --> 00:28:36.619
These are real quotes from a real talk that was given by John D. Cook at GoTo2012.

00:28:36.619 --> 00:28:38.619
And this is not to pick on John D. Cook.

00:28:38.619 --> 00:28:43.619
These were totally reasonable statements at the time.

00:28:43.619 --> 00:28:48.619
And what we found was not just that it was going to be possible to do this in R,

00:28:48.619 --> 00:28:52.619
but it was bizarrely good as a host language for Shiny.

00:28:52.619 --> 00:28:54.619
Bizarrely good.

00:28:54.619 --> 00:29:01.619
And I feel like that's sort of an extraordinary claim, so I will provide some evidence.

00:29:01.619 --> 00:29:08.619
It's going to get a little bit geeky, so just be ready for the shift in tone.

00:29:08.619 --> 00:29:13.619
A lot of languages have positional and named arguments, programming languages.

00:29:13.619 --> 00:29:16.619
A positional arg, like you see here, is like X, right?

00:29:16.619 --> 00:29:17.619
There's no name.

00:29:17.619 --> 00:29:21.619
You just put it with the right number of commas, and it gets matched up.

00:29:21.619 --> 00:29:25.619
And then you have named arguments where you specify exactly what parameter you're passing.

00:29:25.619 --> 00:29:28.619
Height equals 20 in this case.

00:29:28.619 --> 00:29:32.619
And tons of languages, tons of languages have both positional and named arguments.

00:29:32.619 --> 00:29:38.619
But what almost none of them have, none that are in current use that I could find,

00:29:38.619 --> 00:29:43.619
R allows the named arguments to be passed first.

00:29:43.619 --> 00:29:45.619
Super random, weird quirk.

00:29:45.619 --> 00:29:47.619
Nobody does this.

00:29:47.619 --> 00:29:51.619
This is not considered a best practice.

00:29:51.619 --> 00:29:52.619
Python doesn't do it.

00:29:52.619 --> 00:29:53.619
Ruby doesn't do it.

00:29:53.619 --> 00:29:54.619
C Sharp doesn't do it.

00:29:54.619 --> 00:30:00.619
None of these languages that have both named and positional args let you put them in this order.

00:30:00.619 --> 00:30:03.619
And by the way, in R, you can put it in whatever order you can mix them.

00:30:03.619 --> 00:30:08.619
It's R, you know.

00:30:08.619 --> 00:30:10.619
And this matters for Shiny.

00:30:10.619 --> 00:30:16.619
It matters for Shiny because a lot of what the UI layer of Shiny does is express HTML.

00:30:16.619 --> 00:30:19.619
And think about how you express HTML if you're familiar with HTML.

00:30:19.619 --> 00:30:23.619
If not, hopefully you'll be able to follow along.

00:30:23.619 --> 00:30:26.619
An HTML tag really lets you express three things.

00:30:26.619 --> 00:30:27.619
The tag itself.

00:30:27.619 --> 00:30:32.619
In this case, on the outside, we have a UL tag for an unordered list.

00:30:32.619 --> 00:30:38.619
Secondly, the attributes for that tag describing, well, attributes about the tag.

00:30:38.619 --> 00:30:43.619
In this case, it's saying that this unordered list is for the purpose of navigation.

00:30:43.619 --> 00:30:45.619
And third and last, you have children.

00:30:45.619 --> 00:30:48.619
What are the things that are contained inside of this tag?

00:30:48.619 --> 00:30:51.619
But this order is the right order.

00:30:51.619 --> 00:30:52.619
This is the way we think about it, right?

00:30:52.619 --> 00:30:53.619
What am I making?

00:30:53.619 --> 00:30:54.619
A UL.

00:30:54.619 --> 00:30:55.619
What are the attributes of that UL?

00:30:55.619 --> 00:30:56.619
It's a nav.

00:30:56.619 --> 00:30:57.619
And then what's inside the UL?

00:30:57.619 --> 00:30:59.619
Children.

00:30:59.619 --> 00:31:06.619
So if this is the structure we're aiming at, how closely can we match that in R?

00:31:06.619 --> 00:31:08.619
Pretty close, as it turns out.

00:31:08.619 --> 00:31:10.619
Pretty close.

00:31:11.619 --> 00:31:16.619
It almost looks like we've just taken away some angle brackets and added some parentheses.

00:31:16.619 --> 00:31:17.619
And some commas.

00:31:17.619 --> 00:31:19.619
Sorry about the commas.

00:31:19.619 --> 00:31:20.619
It's the same order.

00:31:20.619 --> 00:31:22.619
UL first.

00:31:22.619 --> 00:31:24.619
Attributes second.

00:31:24.619 --> 00:31:28.619
Children third.

00:31:28.619 --> 00:31:36.619
And it's only because we're allowed to put the named arguments that we're using for attributes first.

00:31:36.619 --> 00:31:43.619
So just to take a language at random...

00:31:43.619 --> 00:31:45.619
Let's talk about Python.

00:31:45.619 --> 00:31:48.619
Python has named arguments, but they have to go last.

00:31:48.619 --> 00:31:52.619
So we end up with tag first.

00:31:52.619 --> 00:31:54.619
Attributes at the bottom.

00:31:54.619 --> 00:31:57.619
And then all the children.

00:31:57.619 --> 00:32:02.619
And that is a problem, because it adds all this space that you have to look past

00:32:02.619 --> 00:32:05.619
in order to find out what kind of a UL you're creating.

00:32:05.619 --> 00:32:08.619
This example is just 12 lines, but you can imagine if this is a production dashboard,

00:32:08.619 --> 00:32:13.619
it might be screenfuls that you have to traverse.

00:32:13.619 --> 00:32:16.619
So I don't want to put up the weakest straw man possible,

00:32:16.619 --> 00:32:19.619
so let's steel man it a little bit.

00:32:19.619 --> 00:32:26.619
So here is one option that you could use in Python to improve the situation.

00:32:26.619 --> 00:32:28.619
You could get rid of named arguments altogether

00:32:28.619 --> 00:32:30.619
and express everything with positional arguments.

00:32:30.619 --> 00:32:31.619
And you could do that.

00:32:31.619 --> 00:32:34.619
You could put a dictionary at the top.

00:32:34.619 --> 00:32:37.619
Similar to like a named list, I guess.

00:32:37.619 --> 00:32:39.619
And this would work.

00:32:39.619 --> 00:32:41.619
It adds some curly braces.

00:32:41.619 --> 00:32:43.619
It adds some quotation marks.

00:32:43.619 --> 00:32:46.619
So it's not perfect, but it certainly works.

00:32:46.619 --> 00:32:47.619
I'm not going to argue it doesn't work.

00:32:47.619 --> 00:32:52.619
I would call this maybe 85% as good as what you can do in R.

00:32:52.619 --> 00:32:56.619
The other way you go in Python is to go all named arguments.

00:32:56.619 --> 00:32:58.619
So you don't pass children as unnamed arguments.

00:32:58.619 --> 00:33:04.619
Instead, you make a named argument called children and give it a list.

00:33:04.619 --> 00:33:06.619
Again, the details here aren't important.

00:33:06.619 --> 00:33:09.619
The point is that...

00:33:09.619 --> 00:33:11.619
Well, the point is it's worse, I guess.

00:33:11.619 --> 00:33:12.619
That's the point.

00:33:12.619 --> 00:33:16.619
And this one, to me, is worse than the previous one

00:33:16.619 --> 00:33:18.619
because it actually pushes the code off the page.

00:33:18.619 --> 00:33:21.619
We've added a line, a vertical line,

00:33:21.619 --> 00:33:26.619
and a level of indentation for each level of children at this point.

00:33:27.619 --> 00:33:31.619
And also, switching from UI to reactivity,

00:33:31.619 --> 00:33:35.619
nonstandard evaluation ended up being weirdly, bizarrely good

00:33:35.619 --> 00:33:36.619
for reactive programming,

00:33:36.619 --> 00:33:40.619
not something that we had anticipated.

00:33:40.619 --> 00:33:42.619
This is what my sort of...

00:33:42.619 --> 00:33:43.619
If I could wave that magic wand

00:33:43.619 --> 00:33:45.619
and have a language to express reactivity in,

00:33:45.619 --> 00:33:47.619
it might look something like this.

00:33:47.619 --> 00:33:49.619
I want a language keyword for the word reactive.

00:33:49.619 --> 00:33:51.619
That's an important concept.

00:33:51.619 --> 00:33:55.619
I want to attach a code block to that keyword.

00:33:55.619 --> 00:33:57.619
And then reading something out of a reactive expression,

00:33:57.619 --> 00:33:59.619
like read data, say,

00:33:59.619 --> 00:34:01.619
I want a star operator,

00:34:01.619 --> 00:34:04.619
sort of like dereferencing a pointer in C.

00:34:04.619 --> 00:34:07.619
So this is kind of what, you know,

00:34:07.619 --> 00:34:08.620
if I got my wish,

00:34:08.620 --> 00:34:11.620
this is what a perfect language for reactivity would look like.

00:34:11.620 --> 00:34:13.620
And let's see what we have in R.

00:34:13.620 --> 00:34:17.620
It's pretty close.

00:34:17.620 --> 00:34:20.620
In Python, we have to go a different way.

00:34:20.620 --> 00:34:22.620
Python does not have nonstandard evaluation,

00:34:22.620 --> 00:34:27.620
so you can't pass a bare block of code to a function

00:34:27.620 --> 00:34:30.620
and expect it to be anything but a value

00:34:30.620 --> 00:34:33.620
by the time the function gets at it.

00:34:33.620 --> 00:34:35.620
Instead, in Python, you have to write a function,

00:34:35.620 --> 00:34:36.620
a named function,

00:34:36.620 --> 00:34:40.620
and then you have to apply reactivity to it.

00:34:40.620 --> 00:34:43.620
Now, again, I don't want to leave you with a straw man,

00:34:43.620 --> 00:34:44.620
so here's the steel man.

00:34:44.620 --> 00:34:47.620
Python has a few tricks of its own up its sleeve,

00:34:47.620 --> 00:34:49.620
and this is called a decorator.

00:34:49.620 --> 00:34:51.620
And you know what? This is not bad.

00:34:51.620 --> 00:34:56.620
I'll say this is maybe like 90% as good as R.

00:34:56.620 --> 00:34:58.620
I still don't love that it's a function.

00:34:58.620 --> 00:34:59.620
It feels like you made a function,

00:34:59.620 --> 00:35:00.620
and then you made it reactive,

00:35:00.620 --> 00:35:02.620
and I really prefer how it looks in R,

00:35:02.620 --> 00:35:06.620
where it sort of feels like you constructed a reactive.

00:35:06.620 --> 00:35:08.620
But I'm not going to argue that this doesn't work

00:35:08.620 --> 00:35:10.620
and doesn't have appeal to people

00:35:10.620 --> 00:35:12.620
who come from this tradition.

00:35:12.620 --> 00:35:18.620
Okay, so can we even build it in R?

00:35:18.620 --> 00:35:20.620
R is the best language for Shiny.

00:35:20.620 --> 00:35:21.620
I will die on this hill.

00:35:21.620 --> 00:35:28.620
R is the best language for Shiny.

00:35:28.620 --> 00:35:33.620
So those three big questions were answered.

00:35:33.620 --> 00:35:35.620
Can we even build it in R?

00:35:35.620 --> 00:35:37.620
R is the best language for Shiny.

00:35:37.620 --> 00:35:39.620
Are R users ready to write web apps?

00:35:39.620 --> 00:35:42.620
R has the best audience for Shiny.

00:35:42.620 --> 00:35:44.620
And will the R community respond

00:35:45.620 --> 00:35:51.620
to almost an absurd degree you have responded?

00:35:51.620 --> 00:35:57.620
So yes, Shiny has been a success.

00:35:57.620 --> 00:36:00.620
So I hope that I've convinced you,

00:36:00.620 --> 00:36:02.620
or at least I've convinced you that I am convinced

00:36:02.620 --> 00:36:07.620
that R is the best language for Shiny.

00:36:07.620 --> 00:36:12.620
But you know what they say about Python.

00:36:12.620 --> 00:36:14.620
Python is the second best language for anything.

00:36:14.620 --> 00:36:24.620
Python is the second best language for anything.

00:36:24.620 --> 00:36:25.620
And that is not an insult.

00:36:25.620 --> 00:36:27.620
That is a compliment.

00:36:27.620 --> 00:36:30.620
That quote was popularized by Dan Callahan at PyCon 2018.

00:36:30.620 --> 00:36:32.620
During a keynote, he said,

00:36:32.620 --> 00:36:34.620
Python is the second best language for anything,

00:36:34.620 --> 00:36:37.620
and that is an amazing aspiration.

00:36:37.620 --> 00:36:40.620
Because it means that whatever domain you're operating in,

00:36:40.620 --> 00:36:43.620
whatever weird new technique in computing

00:36:43.620 --> 00:36:45.620
you're interested in,

00:36:45.620 --> 00:36:46.620
there's a pretty good chance

00:36:46.620 --> 00:36:49.620
that you can stitch something together in Python.

00:36:49.620 --> 00:36:52.620
And it might not be the very best version

00:36:52.620 --> 00:36:54.620
or the very best expression of that idea,

00:36:54.620 --> 00:36:58.620
but it will be available to you without going somewhere else.

00:36:58.620 --> 00:37:04.620
And there is undoubtedly power in that.

00:37:04.620 --> 00:37:07.620
So introducing Shiny for Python.

00:37:07.620 --> 00:37:20.620
audience members cheering and applauding

00:37:20.620 --> 00:37:23.620
Like 45% of you are real excited.

00:37:23.620 --> 00:37:29.620
audience laughing

00:37:29.620 --> 00:37:33.620
Here is an app running in Shiny for Python.

00:37:33.620 --> 00:37:38.620
This is sort of our July 31st, 2012 moment for Shiny for R.

00:37:38.620 --> 00:37:45.620
That's about where we are today with Shiny for Python.

00:37:45.620 --> 00:37:47.620
I don't expect you to be able to read this code,

00:37:47.620 --> 00:37:51.620
but if you could, and you know Shiny for R

00:37:51.620 --> 00:37:52.620
and you know a little bit of Python,

00:37:52.620 --> 00:37:55.620
this is going to look pretty familiar.

00:37:55.620 --> 00:37:58.620
There are a lot of concepts that carry through between the two,

00:37:58.620 --> 00:38:02.620
even though we are dealing with two separate languages.

00:38:02.620 --> 00:38:05.620
And the server side is filled

00:38:05.620 --> 00:38:07.620
with the same kind of reactive concepts

00:38:07.620 --> 00:38:11.620
that you're used to from Shiny for R.

00:38:11.620 --> 00:38:13.620
And before we go further, I have to warn you,

00:38:13.620 --> 00:38:16.620
this is an alpha, and it's especially alpha

00:38:16.620 --> 00:38:19.620
because we did all this work in secret.

00:38:19.620 --> 00:38:21.620
And we're not used to doing that.

00:38:21.620 --> 00:38:23.620
None of us really like it.

00:38:23.620 --> 00:38:27.620
We're really happy to not have to do it after today.

00:38:28.620 --> 00:38:33.620
So we are not ready to call something out of alpha

00:38:33.620 --> 00:38:36.620
until the community has had a chance to bang on it

00:38:36.620 --> 00:38:39.620
and we still reserve the right to change the API.

00:38:39.620 --> 00:38:42.620
So I'm going to give you that warning.

00:38:42.620 --> 00:38:45.620
Our design philosophy for Shiny for Python

00:38:45.620 --> 00:38:49.620
was that it's very similar conceptually to Shiny for R.

00:38:49.620 --> 00:38:51.620
And that wasn't necessarily a first principle

00:38:51.620 --> 00:38:52.620
that we started with.

00:38:52.620 --> 00:38:54.620
We were open to changing our ideas

00:38:54.620 --> 00:38:58.620
as we moved from R to Python and vice versa.

00:38:58.620 --> 00:39:00.620
But I think what we found

00:39:00.620 --> 00:39:03.620
was a lot of the trade-offs that we had made in R

00:39:03.620 --> 00:39:04.620
were pretty universal,

00:39:04.620 --> 00:39:06.620
and they felt pretty good in Python.

00:39:06.620 --> 00:39:08.620
But it's not a slavishly literal port from R.

00:39:08.620 --> 00:39:10.620
We don't want Shiny for Python

00:39:10.620 --> 00:39:13.620
to feel like it was written by R users.

00:39:13.620 --> 00:39:18.620
We want it to feel idiomatically like Python.

00:39:18.620 --> 00:39:22.620
So to give an example of what I mean when I say, you know,

00:39:22.620 --> 00:39:25.620
Python is the second-best language for anything,

00:39:25.620 --> 00:39:29.620
I tapped our resident astrophysicist,

00:39:29.620 --> 00:39:30.620
Dr. Julia Silgit.

00:39:30.620 --> 00:39:33.620
Not a joke.

00:39:33.620 --> 00:39:35.620
And I asked her, you know,

00:39:35.620 --> 00:39:37.620
I hear Python maybe is big in astronomy.

00:39:37.620 --> 00:39:40.620
Is there something we could do with a Shiny app for that?

00:39:40.620 --> 00:39:44.620
And she had this idea for an air mass calculator.

00:39:44.620 --> 00:39:46.620
And long story short,

00:39:46.620 --> 00:39:49.620
this lets you provide a list of astronomical objects

00:39:49.620 --> 00:39:51.620
you're interested in observing on a certain day

00:39:51.620 --> 00:39:54.620
and from a certain location on Earth.

00:39:54.620 --> 00:39:56.620
And this calculator will tell you

00:39:56.620 --> 00:40:00.620
what times of night are optimal for viewing that object,

00:40:00.620 --> 00:40:05.620
including...

00:40:05.620 --> 00:40:08.620
I'm not an astronomer.

00:40:08.620 --> 00:40:11.620
How much air lies along your line of sight

00:40:11.620 --> 00:40:13.620
between you and the object you're viewing?

00:40:13.620 --> 00:40:15.620
Because depending on its angle from the horizon,

00:40:15.620 --> 00:40:18.620
you're going through a different amount of atmosphere.

00:40:18.620 --> 00:40:23.620
So that's what this air mass calculator is showing you.

00:40:23.620 --> 00:40:27.620
Super easy to do because of AstroPy.

00:40:27.620 --> 00:40:32.620
And super easy to turn into this app because of Shiny.

00:40:32.620 --> 00:40:35.620
So Shiny for Python, again, alpha.

00:40:35.620 --> 00:40:36.620
It is available now.

00:40:36.620 --> 00:40:39.620
If you go to shiny.rstudio.com slash py,

00:40:39.620 --> 00:40:41.620
you will find lots of documentation.

00:40:41.620 --> 00:40:42.620
There are examples.

00:40:42.620 --> 00:40:43.620
There's articles.

00:40:43.620 --> 00:40:47.620
There's API docs.

00:40:47.620 --> 00:40:50.620
And I want to talk a little bit about editor support.

00:40:50.620 --> 00:40:52.620
We expect that most people are probably

00:40:52.620 --> 00:40:54.620
going to be writing these things in VS Code,

00:40:54.620 --> 00:40:56.620
and we've written an extension

00:40:56.620 --> 00:40:59.620
for authoring Shiny for Python in VS Code.

00:40:59.620 --> 00:41:02.620
If you use something else like PyCharm or JupyterLab,

00:41:02.620 --> 00:41:03.620
that should work too.

00:41:03.620 --> 00:41:08.620
We're a pretty standard Python web framework in that respect.

00:41:08.620 --> 00:41:10.620
RStudio IDE is going to get basic support

00:41:10.620 --> 00:41:13.620
for Shiny for Python apps in the next release.

00:41:14.620 --> 00:41:17.620
That'll be mostly in the form of a run app button.

00:41:17.620 --> 00:41:19.620
And if you are using RStudio Workbench

00:41:19.620 --> 00:41:21.620
to have RStudio on the server,

00:41:21.620 --> 00:41:24.620
then the VS Code and JupyterLab versions

00:41:24.620 --> 00:41:28.620
that are run on RStudio Workbench work great

00:41:28.620 --> 00:41:31.620
if you have the current release of RStudio Workbench

00:41:31.620 --> 00:41:35.620
spotted wake Robin.

