00:48:58.620 --> 00:49:00.620
So, first question for you, Joe,

00:49:00.620 --> 00:49:03.620
how did you come up with the name Shiny?

00:49:04.620 --> 00:49:05.620
Yes.

00:49:05.620 --> 00:49:11.620
So, the name Shiny comes from a show called Firefly.

00:49:11.620 --> 00:49:21.620
A few months before Shiny, you know, became a thing,

00:49:21.620 --> 00:49:24.620
I was laying sick in bed, and I watched the whole series Firefly

00:49:24.620 --> 00:49:28.620
for the first time, and they used the word shiny to mean good.

00:49:29.620 --> 00:49:31.620
They'll say, yeah, I'm feeling shiny.

00:49:31.620 --> 00:49:33.620
Yeah, this job is going really shiny.

00:49:33.620 --> 00:49:35.620
And I just thought, like, oh, that's,

00:49:35.620 --> 00:49:37.620
I like how they just sort of slipped that in all casual,

00:49:37.620 --> 00:49:40.620
and I thought that'd be a cool name for a project someday.

00:49:41.620 --> 00:49:44.620
The day that I was creating the GitHub repo

00:49:44.620 --> 00:49:48.620
for the first commit of what was to become Shiny,

00:49:48.620 --> 00:49:51.620
on GitHub, there's a little name suggester, right?

00:49:51.620 --> 00:49:53.620
It says, like, having trouble thinking of a name?

00:49:53.620 --> 00:49:54.620
It's blah, blah, blah.

00:49:54.620 --> 00:49:55.620
And it's three segments.

00:49:55.620 --> 00:49:57.620
I don't remember the first segment, but it was like,

00:49:57.620 --> 00:50:00.620
it was something like Ninja, Octocat, Shiny.

00:50:00.620 --> 00:50:03.620
And I was like, all right, that's a sign from God.

00:50:03.620 --> 00:50:04.620
It's shiny.

00:50:04.620 --> 00:50:06.620
That's what it's going to be.

00:50:07.620 --> 00:50:09.620
Oh.

00:50:09.620 --> 00:50:11.620
I know I've asked you this question myself.

00:50:11.620 --> 00:50:15.620
What do you think of people calling Shiny, R Shiny?

00:50:19.620 --> 00:50:22.620
Yeah, I think maybe Dean Attali popularized this

00:50:22.620 --> 00:50:25.620
and just felt like, hey, it's more clear,

00:50:25.620 --> 00:50:29.620
and he really was successful in popularizing it.

00:50:29.620 --> 00:50:32.620
And I think for people internal to RStudio,

00:50:32.620 --> 00:50:34.620
they'd frequently ask, hey, is it R Shiny or is it Shiny?

00:50:34.620 --> 00:50:35.620
And I said, it's Shiny.

00:50:35.620 --> 00:50:36.620
It's not R Shiny.

00:50:36.620 --> 00:50:37.620
It's just Shiny.

00:50:37.620 --> 00:50:40.620
And so I think, like, all of us sort of developed

00:50:40.620 --> 00:50:42.620
a little bit of an aversion to R Shiny.

00:50:42.620 --> 00:50:44.620
But now that there's Shiny for Python,

00:50:44.620 --> 00:50:46.620
it's going to be hard not to call it R Shiny.

00:50:46.620 --> 00:50:49.620
So I've made my peace with it.

00:50:49.620 --> 00:50:52.620
So what about, obviously, other similar frameworks

00:50:52.620 --> 00:50:54.620
like Dash and Streamlet?

00:50:54.620 --> 00:50:56.620
Why Shiny for Python?

00:50:56.620 --> 00:50:57.620
Yeah, totally.

00:50:57.620 --> 00:50:58.620
It's a valid question,

00:50:58.620 --> 00:51:00.620
and it's a really interesting question

00:51:00.620 --> 00:51:03.620
we didn't have to face with Shiny for R.

00:51:04.620 --> 00:51:09.620
I think that there, as these frameworks were coming out,

00:51:09.620 --> 00:51:11.620
we looked at them, each one of them,

00:51:11.620 --> 00:51:14.620
and we were curious,

00:51:14.620 --> 00:51:16.620
not even from a competitive point of view,

00:51:16.620 --> 00:51:19.620
but just out of curiosity, what were their approaches?

00:51:19.620 --> 00:51:21.620
What tradeoffs had they chosen?

00:51:21.620 --> 00:51:24.620
And it turned out that despite the proliferation

00:51:24.620 --> 00:51:27.620
of these kinds of web frameworks and Python,

00:51:27.620 --> 00:51:29.620
all of the tradeoffs that they chose

00:51:29.620 --> 00:51:31.620
were actually quite different

00:51:31.620 --> 00:51:32.620
than what we were doing with Shiny.

00:51:32.620 --> 00:51:36.620
And I think the kinds of apps that I see people build,

00:51:36.620 --> 00:51:38.620
people in this room,

00:51:38.620 --> 00:51:42.620
a lot of them would actually be difficult to build

00:51:42.620 --> 00:51:45.620
given the tradeoffs inherent in those other...

00:51:45.620 --> 00:51:48.620
You know, this is not, like, a Python conference.

00:51:48.620 --> 00:51:49.620
It's not PositCon.

00:51:49.620 --> 00:51:51.620
It's, you know, it's RStudioCon,

00:51:51.620 --> 00:51:53.620
so I don't want to belabor it,

00:51:53.620 --> 00:51:57.620
but I do want to say that there are real differences,

00:51:57.620 --> 00:52:00.620
and I think that there is room for...

00:52:00.620 --> 00:52:02.620
We think that there's room for something new

00:52:02.620 --> 00:52:04.620
in the Python world.

00:52:04.620 --> 00:52:08.620
Someone related, what about PyScript?

00:52:08.620 --> 00:52:11.620
Oh, the new thing that Peter Wang presented.

00:52:11.620 --> 00:52:16.620
Yes, so PyScript is a really interesting piece of technology

00:52:16.620 --> 00:52:18.620
that sort of goes the other way.

00:52:18.620 --> 00:52:21.620
It lets you take an HTML page, you know,

00:52:21.620 --> 00:52:23.620
that might have JavaScript, might have whatever in it,

00:52:23.620 --> 00:52:27.620
and it lets you embed Python snippets of code

00:52:27.620 --> 00:52:31.620
into your JavaScript apps, basically.

00:52:31.620 --> 00:52:33.620
I think they want to replace JavaScript

00:52:33.620 --> 00:52:37.620
as the language of directly manipulating web apps.

00:52:37.620 --> 00:52:39.620
So that replaces one part of the stack.

00:52:39.620 --> 00:52:41.620
It replaces the language JavaScript

00:52:41.620 --> 00:52:43.620
with the language Python.

00:52:43.620 --> 00:52:47.620
So I think that's an interesting endeavor

00:52:47.620 --> 00:52:50.620
and certainly very impressive technically

00:52:50.620 --> 00:52:54.620
and quite different than I think what we're trying to do,

00:52:54.620 --> 00:52:57.620
which is to go from Python

00:52:57.620 --> 00:53:00.620
and sort of relieve you

00:53:00.620 --> 00:53:02.620
from having to have to think about the entire stack.

00:53:02.620 --> 00:53:05.620
So the orchestration of how data moves back and forth

00:53:05.620 --> 00:53:07.620
between the server and the client,

00:53:07.620 --> 00:53:10.620
there are just a lot of things that are part of our stack

00:53:10.620 --> 00:53:14.620
that PyScript is just out of scope.

00:53:14.620 --> 00:53:18.620
Now, you mentioned that we might be able to run Python,

00:53:18.620 --> 00:53:22.620
Shiny for Python, but out of server.

00:53:22.620 --> 00:53:26.620
What about Shiny for R?

00:53:26.620 --> 00:53:28.620
We sure hope.

00:53:28.620 --> 00:53:30.620
We sure hope so.

00:53:30.620 --> 00:53:34.620
The thing is that right now,

00:53:34.620 --> 00:53:37.620
the technology that this...

00:53:37.620 --> 00:53:41.620
Is it okay if I say the word?

00:53:41.620 --> 00:53:43.620
This approach that we're taking for running in the browser

00:53:43.620 --> 00:53:45.620
is called Wasm.

00:53:45.620 --> 00:53:51.620
And Python is the second best language for Wasm, yeah.

00:53:51.620 --> 00:53:52.620
Those guys, every time.

00:53:52.620 --> 00:53:54.620
Yeah, they're the second best language for Wasm.

00:53:54.620 --> 00:53:57.620
Yeah, Rust is probably number one.

00:53:57.620 --> 00:54:00.620
So the question really is about,

00:54:00.620 --> 00:54:02.620
is R going to have Wasm?

00:54:02.620 --> 00:54:05.620
And the answer is...

00:54:05.620 --> 00:54:08.620
Why don't you answer that?

00:54:08.620 --> 00:54:11.620
Yes, so that is something that we're going to be working on.

00:54:11.620 --> 00:54:12.620
You might want to...

00:54:12.620 --> 00:54:15.620
George Stagg, who's recently joined our studio,

00:54:15.620 --> 00:54:17.620
is giving a lightning talk about this.

00:54:17.620 --> 00:54:20.620
So we are actively working to bring Wasm for R

00:54:20.620 --> 00:54:22.620
so you can take any R application

00:54:22.620 --> 00:54:26.620
and compile it to JavaScript, basically.

00:54:26.620 --> 00:54:33.620
applause

00:54:33.620 --> 00:54:35.620
I feel like we just did a really bad version

00:54:35.620 --> 00:54:39.620
of, like, Winston's and George's talk.

00:54:39.620 --> 00:54:41.620
Sorry, you should check them out.

00:54:41.620 --> 00:54:42.620
It's going to be pretty exciting.

00:54:42.620 --> 00:54:44.620
Okay, I've got a high-stress question for you,

00:54:44.620 --> 00:54:47.620
but I'm going to follow it up with a low-stress question.

00:54:47.620 --> 00:54:49.620
So when will the book that covers

00:54:49.620 --> 00:54:53.620
all of these exciting new features be out, though?

00:54:53.620 --> 00:54:55.620
Whenever Hadley needs a new bike.

00:54:55.620 --> 00:54:58.620
Yeah.

00:54:58.620 --> 00:55:01.620
Would it be possible to use both R and Python

00:55:01.620 --> 00:55:03.620
within a single app?

00:55:03.620 --> 00:55:06.620
Could you use both R and Python in a single app?

00:55:06.620 --> 00:55:09.620
I mean, I suppose you could do something with Reticulate.

00:55:09.620 --> 00:55:12.620
We know you can, because people do use Reticulate

00:55:12.620 --> 00:55:13.620
with Shiny for R,

00:55:13.620 --> 00:55:16.620
and I'm sure the reverse works as well.

00:55:16.620 --> 00:55:18.620
But yeah, definitely not something

00:55:18.620 --> 00:55:23.620
that we have thought a lot about in building Shiny for Python.

00:55:23.620 --> 00:55:26.620
How about other packages in the kind of Shiny ecosystem,

00:55:26.620 --> 00:55:28.620
like Shiny Test 2 and HTML tools?

00:55:28.620 --> 00:55:31.620
Are you going to bring those to Python as well?

00:55:31.620 --> 00:55:33.620
Yeah.

00:55:33.620 --> 00:55:35.620
We sure hope so.

00:55:35.620 --> 00:55:39.620
Again, this is the 2012 moment of Shiny for Python.

00:55:39.620 --> 00:55:41.620
Anything's possible.

00:55:41.620 --> 00:55:43.620
Are those three big questions going to be answered

00:55:43.620 --> 00:55:45.620
the same way in the Python community?

00:55:45.620 --> 00:55:46.620
Nobody knows.

00:55:46.620 --> 00:55:48.620
So I think it would probably be premature

00:55:48.620 --> 00:55:50.620
for me to stand here and say

00:55:50.620 --> 00:55:53.620
that all these things are going to appear.

00:55:53.620 --> 00:55:54.620
But it is certainly our intention,

00:55:54.620 --> 00:55:57.620
if we're successful in the fullness of time,

00:55:57.620 --> 00:55:59.620
for Shiny for Python to be a mature and complete stack

00:55:59.620 --> 00:56:02.620
in the same way that Shiny for R is.

00:56:02.620 --> 00:56:03.620
So sort of following up on that,

00:56:03.620 --> 00:56:06.620
is the plan to have the features develop at the same pace

00:56:06.620 --> 00:56:08.620
for both R and Python in the future?

00:56:08.620 --> 00:56:12.620
Oh, would the features be developed at the same pace?

00:56:12.620 --> 00:56:16.620
Certainly for features where Python is catching up to R,

00:56:16.620 --> 00:56:19.620
naturally it's going to go much faster in Python

00:56:19.620 --> 00:56:20.620
than it ever did in R

00:56:20.620 --> 00:56:23.620
because we're doing everything for a second time.

00:56:23.620 --> 00:56:24.620
It is just much easier

00:56:24.620 --> 00:56:27.620
when you have solved a problem once.

00:56:27.620 --> 00:56:30.620
In terms of new features,

00:56:30.620 --> 00:56:31.620
we haven't really talked about this,

00:56:31.620 --> 00:56:33.620
but I wouldn't want to commit

00:56:33.620 --> 00:56:36.620
to any kind of artificially enforced parity.

00:56:36.620 --> 00:56:38.620
I mean, I think part of the point

00:56:38.620 --> 00:56:40.620
of what we're trying to do here

00:56:40.620 --> 00:56:44.620
is to not focus on keeping these things equal.

00:56:44.620 --> 00:56:46.620
We want them to both be as good as they can be

00:56:46.620 --> 00:56:48.620
for their respective communities.

00:56:48.620 --> 00:56:50.620
And we might make a different set of trade-offs

00:56:50.620 --> 00:56:51.620
if we expected that people

00:56:51.620 --> 00:56:54.620
were going to switch back and forth every day.

00:56:54.620 --> 00:56:57.620
And no doubt there will be some people who do that.

00:56:57.620 --> 00:56:59.620
I mean, maybe even people in this room who do that.

00:56:59.620 --> 00:57:01.620
But I think we really want to optimize

00:57:01.620 --> 00:57:03.620
for if you're spending a lot of time in Shiny for R,

00:57:03.620 --> 00:57:05.620
it feels good as an R user.

00:57:05.620 --> 00:57:07.620
And if you spend a lot of time in Shiny for Python,

00:57:07.620 --> 00:57:08.620
it feels good as a Python user.

00:57:08.620 --> 00:57:10.620
So we are going to try to make each of those frameworks

00:57:10.620 --> 00:57:12.620
as good as they can be.

00:57:12.620 --> 00:57:13.620
man 1 in audience Okay, so we'll finish up

